16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA major question in studies of aesthetic expression is how we can understand and explain similarities and differences among different forms of representation. In the current volume, this question is addressed through the lens of make-believe theory, a philosophical theory broadly introduced by two seminal works – Kendall Walton’s Mimesis as Make-Believe and Gregory Currie's The Nature of Fiction, both published 1990. Since then, make-believe theory has become central in the philosphical discussion of representation. As a first of its kind, the current volume comprises 17 detailed studies of highly different forms of representation, such as novels, plays, TV-series, role games, computer games, lamentation poetry and memoirs. The collection contributes to establishing make-believe theory as a powerful theoretical tool for a wide array of studies traditionally falling under the humanities umbrella.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative. 0aFictionxTechnique. 0aImagination in literature. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aTruth in literature. 4aMake-Believe Theorie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aMake-believe.  afictionality.  aimagination.  arepresentational arts.1 aBareis, J. Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBareis, J. Alexander, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBateman, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunia, Remigius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDadlez, E. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeCoursey, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Cruz, Jason, econtributor.4